discovery commander frederick h 
hauck interrupted the crews schedule on saturday to read aloud a 
letter from a student who wrote that some of americas future is 
riding on you and your crews shoulders 
hauck said he had received the brief letter within the last year 
and a half from phillip j pj morgan of brooklyn ny and 
had talked to the boy by telephone just before thursdays launch of 
the first shuttle since the challenger disaster 32 months ago 
dear mr hauck im a worried 14yearold that is worried 
about the future the letter said i feel that some of 
americas future is riding on you and your crews shoulders i give 
you all the inspiration i can give you because your ride this fall 
means so much to me 
hauck said he thought it was a particularly good letter and 
really sent home to us how much the experiences we have here in 
space can have an effect on the youngsters of america 
he said morgan who graduated from st marks parochial school 
in brooklyn and now attends high school had some concerns about 
the future of america and whether we were still capable of doing 
the things that make us a great country 
hauck thanked the boy for the letter and said he hoped all the 
other youngsters out there not only in america but in other parts 
of the world that may be watching and can see that we are back on 
track and we have a lot of technological benefits that will come in 
the future 
the commander read the letter just after astronaut john m 
lounge had finished conducting a scientific experiment that was 
designed by a high school student 
appearing later on the cbs evening news program young morgan 
said i just meant to like uplift the space program 
