<TEXT>
japan expressed hope for improved relations and eastern european 
nations offered effusive congratulations on saturday after sweeping 
changes in soviet leadership left mikhail gorbachev holding the 
nations top two jobs 
gorbachev already the communist party general secretary took 
over the goverment presidency saturday from andrei a gromyko who 
retired after a 50year career that started under josef stalin 
gorbachev has proposed expanding the powers of the largely 
ceremonial presidency along with slashing the massive party 
apparatus 
in japan foreign ministry officials said they hoped the shakeup 
will produce a new soviet policy toward japan the kyodo news 
service reported saturday 
the countries have never formally resolved their world war ii 
antagonism because of competing claims on a group of islands in the 
kurile chain that soviet troops have occupied since the closing 
days of the war 
there was no immediate response from chinese officials 
east european leaders were quick to shower gorbachev with 
congratulatory telegrams saturday notes were sent from hungarian 
communist leader karoly grosz and president bruno f straub 
czechoslovak president gustav husak polish leader wojciech 
jaruzelski and romanian leader nicolae ceausescu who is scheduled 
to meet with gorbachev next week in moscow 
this is a meaningful expression of the soviet nations esteem 
for your services as a precursor creator and unremitting executor 
of the policy of perestroika openness democratization and new 
thinking jaruzelskis message said polands official pap news 
agency reported 
italian premier ciriaco de mita congratulated gorbachev and said 
he will be able to give a renewed and accentuated push to the 
work of stabilization and reinforcement of international relations 
which you have already undertaken with such effectiveness 
indian president r venkataraman of india said gorbachevs 
outstanding personal contribution to the world peace and 
disarmament created a new climate in international relations 
austrian newspapers saturday said the changes signal a 
strengthening of the gorbachev camp 
successful and surprising coup of the kremlin chief 
gorbachev removes all opponents of his reform policy was the 
headline in the independent kurier austrias second largest daily 
in vienna 
us secretary of state george p shultz said on friday the 
shakeup was difficult to assess immediately 
but he added mr gorbachev is a very strong and determined 
person he has a major reform program that he is working on and if 
there is any message from this it is that he intends to pursue that 
program 
