thousands of people have called an 
atampt phone line during the fourday mission of space shuttle 
discovery to listen in on communications between the orbiting 
astronauts and mission control 
the dialashuttle service is sponsored by the national 
space society through atampts dial it 900 services controlled from 
the companys somerset county technical center here 
atampt spokesman john skalko said the service had been provided 
since the first shuttle flight in april 1981 and since then had 
received more than 7 million calls 
maurice parker a nasa public affairs spokesman said estimates 
of the number of calls during the current flight would be released 
monday but he said it certainly numbered in the thousands 
the service allows callers to listen to live conversations 
between the five crew members and mission control at the johnson 
space center in houston by dialing 9009096272 callers are 
charged 2 for the first minute and 45 cents for each additional 
minute when there is no conversation updates on the progress of 
the flight are provided 
skalko said money raised from the service is spent on 
spacerelated programs the service began two hours before liftoff 
thursday and will end two hours after the shuttle lands monday at 
edwards air force base in california 
