department of conservation and land management said it was decided 
for humanitarian reasons to have the whales killed 
they were severely dehydrated and bruised had liver damage 
blood in their urine and extensive tissue damage he said 
they were in pitiful condition said dave mell a department 
wildlife officer a lot were half buried in the sand 
windblasted and with blistered skins 
they were physically incapable of tolerating a rescue attempt 
and would have died en route 
