a peace accord has been reached between 
the sandinista government and more than 300 members of an indian 
guerrilla group the official newspaper barricada said sunday 
the report in the ruling sandinista party newspaper said 10 
military commanders of the yatama group agreed to a ceasefire on 
saturday 
yatama led by brooklyn rivera and steman fagot includes 
members of several groups of atlantic coast indians who have been 
fighting the government for more than six years the indians began 
fighting the sandinistas when the government forced them to 
relocate 
barricada said the truce accord includes provisions for medical 
and food assistance to 54 wartorn communities of about 50000 
people it said the former guerrillas retained the right to form 
selfdefense groups but promised to cut their ties with yatama 
neither yatama leaders nor indians who had broken away from the 
group were available for comment 
ceasefire talks with the indians began in may about a month 
after the ussupported rebels known as contras reached a 
temporary truce with the leftist government the contras have yet 
to negotiate a lasting peace agreement with managua 
the yatama indians seek a form of selfgovernment for indigenous 
tribes along a 75mile stretch of the atlantic seaboard called the 
mosquito coast they are not part of the nicaraguan resistance the 
umbrella for most contra organizations 
yatama claims it has 2000 combatants but at least 1000 have 
surrendered in a series of incidents since last year the indian 
war has stopped for the most part along the atlantic 
the indian fight against the sandinistas marked by factionalism 
since its beginnings in 1981 started when the leftist government 
tried to impose authority on the isolated traditionally 
independent region 
tens of thousands of miskito rama and sumo indians were forced 
from their tribal lands when the sandinistas said they uncovered a 
plan to oust government representatives in the junglelike region 
thousands fled tribal homelands across the winding coco river 
into honduras the united nations high commissioner for refugees 
reported that most have returned home 
nicaraguan indians also resisted any exercise of authority over 
them by the rightist proamerican somoza dynasty that ruled for 42 
years until the sandinistas came to power in 1979 
