<TEXT>
smithkline beckman corp built its world 
around tagamet an ulcer drug that didnt face competition for its 
first eight years and two years ago was the hottestselling 
medicine anywhere 
today that world is being dismantled 
last year a british company took smithklines premier position 
in the ulcer drug market leaving the philadelphia pharmaceutical 
giant with a 25 percent slide in profits for the second quarter of 
this year 
the company was forced last week to announce a restructuring 
plan that will cost up to 400 million and slash about 1600 jobs 
smithklines problem industry analysts say is its lack of new 
drugs to follow tagamets success 
its every ceos nightmare to have a successful product but 
no followup samuel isaly an analyst with sg warbug amp co in 
new york they were either unlucky or unsmart that they didnt 
have new products to replace the inevitable decline of tagamet 
and dyazide smithklines highly successful blood pressure medicine 
ronald m nordmann an analyst with painewebber inc in new 
york said here we are 24 years later and son of tagamet has yet 
to be developed 
producing a new drug takes several years of research animal 
testing and human trials before it gets the food and drug 
administrations approval for sale work first began on tagamet in 
1964 12 years before it was introduced 
i dont think they have the horses in the stables at this 
point to generate growth nordmann said 
tagamet first hit the british market in 1976 and was introduced 
in the us a year later in 1986 the drug set a record for yearly 
sales of a prescription medication at 1132 billion 
but the competition has been able to catch up with londonbased 
glaxo holdings incs zantac beating tagamet in the ulcer market 
analysts calculate zantac this year has about 40 percent of the 
ulcer drug sales with tagamet at about 30 to 35 percent 
dyazide another smithkline blockbuster hit 365 million in 
sales last year but late in 1987 its first competitor entered the 
market 
smithkline cited dyazides disappointing performance in 
announcing the secondquarter slide in profits but played down 
tagamets role in the reorganization 
tagamet is facing a lot of competition theres no doubt about 
it but if there were less competition and stronger tagamet sales 
than there are i believe we would still be here today talking 
about these decisions henry wendt chief executive officer said 
at a news conference tuesday announcing the restructuring 
analysts however were skeptical about the stated lack of 
effect by tagamet on the situation 
under the restructuring plan smithkline said domestic and 
international drug sales and research which had been the three 
main units of the companys drug business would be consolidated 
while a stronger emphasis would be placed on its other major 
divisions they include beckman instruments diagnostic tools 
allergan inc eye care and smithkline bioscience laboratories 
testing 
about 1600 jobs would be eliminated in the coming years 
including 60 percent of the 500strong corporate staff the company 
said 
the restructuring carries a price tag of 375 to 400 million 
smithkline also said it would sell 17 percent of beckman 
instruments in a public offering of 5 million newly issued shares 
of common stock 
wendt hinted at a possible spinoff of other companies as well 
the plans were received coolly in the days following the 
announcement with the companys stock slipping 3 to 4512 a 
share between tuesday and the close of new york stock exchange 
trading on friday 
the company and analysts expected such public offerings will 
define a high value for the companies and with smithkline 
retaining a majority of the stock the parents market value will 
increase as well 
the restructuring will have an impact on earnings beginning in 
the first three months of next year and yield a savings of about 
100 million each year by 1990 wendt said 
about 40 percent of restructuring cost will cover the costs of 
consolidating manufacuring plants in puerto rico and research in 
suburban philadelphia about 40 percent will be taken up by the 
personnel changes and severance payments and another 20 percent 
will cover other nonrecurring costs associated with the 
reorganization smithkline said 
